\chapter{\uppercase{Comparison of MIRA with other formalisms}}% Main chapter title
\label{chap:comparison} % For referencing the chapter elsewhere, use \ref{Chapter1} 
In this chapter, MIRA is compared with other similar approaches on the ground of imperative logic and the theory of actions. The criteria such as: fundamental or non fundamental imperatives; satisfaction of imperatives; agent reference; representation and evaluation of imperative and actions; and perspective of speaker or addressee or action performance are  compared against MIRA with all other formalisms, described in Chapter \ref{chap:survey}. The uniqueness of MIRA with respect to the rest of other formalisms is also described in this chapter.

\section{\uppercase{Fundamental and Non-fundamental imperatives}}
Hofstadter \& McKinsey (1939), J\"{o}rgensen (1937), and Ross (1941) treat indicatives as a basic unit and imperatives are considered subordinate to it. However, Beardsley (1944), ChrisFox (2008) and Vranas (2008)  view imperatives as a fundamental unit (\ref{sec:implogic}). MIRA also treats imperatives as a fundamental unit, much in line with Vranas approach. 
\section{\uppercase{Satisfaction Criteria in Imperatives}}
Satisfaction criteria vary in some formalisms. These are listed below:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Hofstadter and McKinsey (1939) present a logic of satisfaction of imperatives, wherein the satisfaction criteria is based on whether the imperative is satisfied and not based on agency.
\item ChrisFox (2008) in the work of logic of satisfaction of imperatives, uses a temporal operator to denote the proposition content and then maps it to the satisfaction of the imperative (Section \ref{sec:fox}). 
\item According to Beardsley (1944), satisfaction of an imperative is related to the satisfaction of the desire of the speaker, who is uttering the imperative. 
\item Vranas (2008) provides three values $S$, $V$ and $A$ to address the satisfaction of an imperative. 
\end{enumerate}
MIRA relates imperative to the performance of actions. Hence the satisfaction criteria of an imperative is in direct relation to the action performance, with the agent's intention of achieving the goal, i.e., if the action is performed, the imperative is evaluated to $S$; if not performed, it is evaluated to $V$; and if there is no intention to reach the goal, it is evaluated to $N$.
\section{\uppercase{Agent Reference}}
In formalisms proposed by ChrisFox and Cohen and Levesque, the agent reference is explicitly stated. In the logic of imperatives proposed by ChrisFox (2008), the imperative is broken down to agentive property, which is indicative in nature. Using a temporal operator, this indicative statement is evaluated to a \textit{true} value (Section \ref{sec:fox}). The theory of intention explicitly refer to the agent carrying out the action. This can be seen from Equation \ref{eq:pergoal}, where the agent is referred by the variable $i$. MIRA however, does not explicitly refer to the agent, but it encompasses the agent's intention of achieving the goal. 
\section{\uppercase{Representation and Evaluation of Imperatives and Actions}}
Imperatives and actions are represented using various connectives. Table \ref{tab:conrepmira} lists these representation and the comparison with MIRA is described below:
\subsection{Hofstadter \& McKinsey}
Although MIRA combines imperatives in a similar fashion like Hofstadter \& McKinsey, it is different in these aspects:
\begin{itemize}
\item MIRA does not translate imperatives to propositions, unlike Hofstadter \& McKinsey, who adopt the unary operator `$!$' for translation (Section \ref{sec:fiat}).
\item Hofstadter and McKinsey use the complementary operator $-$. But MIRA does not use the operator for negation, rather treats positive imperatives and negative imperatives as two different sets, inspired by \textit{vidhi} and \textit{ni\d{s}edha} from \mimamsa.
\item Conditional imperatives are categorized into three types in MIRA as imperatives enjoining reason, actions in sequence and goal.
\item MIRA explicitly handles the sequential operation of imperatives $\Rightarrow_i$, whereas  Hofstadter and McKinsey handle the operation of material inclusion.
\item Exclusive disjunction is used in MIRA, whereas inclusive disjunction is adopted by Hofstadter and McKinsey.
\end{itemize}
